{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"18698c7b-f8da-4ea7-a1b6-32cd5e281f5a","content":"Based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI (no relevant docs found in this workspace):\n\n**Both approaches are correct for .NET 10.**\n\n1. **`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — Yes, this is the right way to respect safe area insets on iOS. You'll need the platform-specific namespace:\n   ```xml\n   xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n   ```\n\n2. **`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"`** — Yes, this lets a specific view (like a Grid with a background image) extend into the unsafe area (behind the notch/home indicator) even when the page respects safe areas.\n\n**Typical pattern:**\n```xml\n<ContentPage ...\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n    <Grid IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\">\n        <Image Source=\"background.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n    </Grid>\n    <!-- Other content respects safe area -->\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nThis way your content avoids the notch, but the background image fills edge-to-edge.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aebb1e8b-47f9-45e3-8d27-56a51337e161","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The working directory appears to be empty and doesn't contain any relevant MAUI code. Let me answer based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI safe area APIs.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the safe area handling has evolved:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - This is the **iOS platform-specific** attached property from `Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific`. It's been available since early .NET MAUI and tells the page to respect the safe area insets (avoiding the notch, home indicator, etc.). This is still valid in .NET 10.\n\n\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - This property lets individual views break out of the safe area constraints, useful when you want something like a background image to extend behind the notch. The `Page.UseSafeArea` property requires the iOS platform-specific namespace prefix in XAML, typically declared as `xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific`.\n\nI'm second-guessing myself on `IgnoreSafeArea` though—I'm not certain it exists as a direct property in .NET MAUI, and the safe area handling may have changed between Xamarin.Forms and the current MAUI versions. I'm second-guessing myself on whether `IgnoreSafeArea` is actually a built-in XAML property or if extending into the safe area requires a different approach like negative margins. Since I don't have the documentation in front of me, I'll go with what I'm confident about: `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` is definitely the right approach for .NET MAUI on .NET 10, and `IgnoreSafeArea` should work for individual views in recent versions, though I'm less certain about that one.","outputTokens":1249,"requestId":"A860:4804C:719FF1:8350CC:69FBE5EA"},"id":"8d7a6197-75c4-4be9-acf0-b2996d94145d","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:08:18.286Z","parentId":"feca80de-8d67-4dab-b832-7f36f11903b3"}
